<body>
	<div class="banner">
		<center><font color="white" size="16px" face="arial">CysB</font></center>
	</div>
	<div align="center" class="main-content">
		<div class="spacer">
	</div><br>			<label class="collapse_ACT" for="_1"><font size="5px">CysB transcriptional activity</font></label>
				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>In our data set , CysB displayed signiﬁcant upregulation during acid adaptation and challenge .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26386064" target="_blank">26386064</a>]<br></li>
<li>All other cys operons had very low activity on swim plates and were induced in swarm conditions , consistent with CysB activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18957594" target="_blank">18957594</a>]<br></li>
<li>Proteins lacking 16 or 22 residues in CysB and OxyR , respectively , were mainly affected in repression but were constitutively active .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24659766" target="_blank">24659766</a>]<br></li>
<li>Ser54 corresponds to Ser35 in AmpR , Ser33 in OxyR , and Ser38 in CysB and GcvA , and these residues are required for DNA binding but not oligomerization ( 27 , 43 -- 45 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24659766" target="_blank">24659766</a>]<br></li>
<li>A different effect was observed for mutants with a A233V point mutation in OxyR and a A227D point mutation in CysB , which still repressed and activated transcription constitutively and bound DNA as dimers ( 9 , 31 , 43 -- 45 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24659766" target="_blank">24659766</a>]<br></li>
<li>The active form of most characterized LTTRs ( NahR , CysB , OxyR , CbnR , DntR , ArgP , TsaR , and AphB ) is a tetramer ( 28 , 30 -- 35 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24659766" target="_blank">24659766</a>]<br></li>
<li>The resultant one-protein complexes contain CysB bound at either CBS-KI or CBS-P1 and can activate transcription initiation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8206845" target="_blank">8206845</a>]<br></li>
<li>Steric hindrance would probably prevent binding of second CysB to a complex already containing a CysB bound to both sites , and if such a complex were formed , we would expect its electrophoretic mobility to increase with N-acetyl-L-serine , which it does not .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8206845" target="_blank">8206845</a>]<br></li>
<li>Activation sites , as well as CBS-J2 and CBS-P2 , are recognized by two CysB subunits related by dyad symmetry , and N-acetyl-L-serine alters CysB to increase binding afﬁnity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>In our model , N-acetyl-L-serine decreases bending by causing CysB to-bind only to a single site , either CBS-K1 or CBS-P1 , and these species activate transcription initiation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8206845" target="_blank">8206845</a>]<br></li>
<li>We can not yet say whether this complex contains one or two CysB protein molecules , but in either case binding to CBS-P3 inhibits binding to the overlapping CBS-P1 and CBS-P2 sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>Acetyl-L-serine stimulates binding of CysB protein to CBS-P2 but inhibits binding to CBS-K2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this case , however , acetyl-L-serine inhibits binding to CBS-K2 , making it likely that the fast complex contains only a single CysB protein molecule bound to CBS-K1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>At relatively low CysB protein concentrations , O-acetyl-L-serine would cause a single CysB protein molecule to-bind tightly to CBS-P1 , rather than to CBS-P3 , thereby decreasing DNA bending and increasing complex electrophoretic mobility .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>Acetyl-L-serine stimulates binding to the sites required for positive regulation , i.e. , CBS-K1 and CBS-P1 , and also decreases or eliminates DNA bending , giving rise to fast complexes , which also contain only a single CysB protein molecule .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>striking differences between these sites is that acetyl-L-serine stimulates CysB protein binding to CBS-J and CBS-K1 and , as demonstrated in this report , inhibits CysB protein binding to CBS-B .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1706701" target="_blank">1706701</a>]<br></li>
<li>Taken together , our results suggests that CysB regulates expression of cysJIH operon to produce H2S , which could acts as a cellular protector during oxidative-stress in S. Typhimurium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25637663" target="_blank">25637663</a>]<br></li>
<li>Microarray analysis of E. coli during sulfur starvation found increased expression of ahpCF encoding an alkyl hydroperoxide reductase positively regulated by OxyR , and the CysB regulon has been shown by microarray analysis to be expressed in cells stressed by methyl viologen ( Blanchard et al. , 2007 ; Gyaneshwar et al. , 2005 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20600858" target="_blank">20600858</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of genes involved in cysteine biosynthesis is controlled by the LysR-type transcriptional-regulator CysB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18957594" target="_blank">18957594</a>]<br></li>
<li>In Escherichia coli , sbp is positively regulated by Cbl , a transcriptional-regulator with 60 % amino acid similarity to CysB , involved in the regulation of cysteine biosynthesis from organic sulfur sources ( Kredich , 1996 ; Stec et al. , 2006 ; Van Der Ploeg et al. , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18957594" target="_blank">18957594</a>]<br></li>
<li>Arginine decarboxylase expression is increased by CysB binding its promoter , and cysB mutants do not ferment many carbohydrates as well as the parent strains of E. coli and S. typhimurium ( Quan et al. , 2002 ; Shi & Bennett , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18957594" target="_blank">18957594</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this way , CysB protein could provide dual control of cysK by activating the major promoter through an interaction at CBS-K1 when sulfur is limiting and by repressing the minor promoter by steric effects at CBS-K1 and CBS-K2 when sulfur is replete .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2254265" target="_blank">2254265</a>]<br></li>
<li>and the catabolite repressor -RCB- activator ( Cra ) protein ( Saier & Ramseier , 1996 ; Saier et al. , 1996 ) , nitrogen utilization is controlled by the NtrBC sensor kinase -RCB- response-regulator pair in conjunction with the GlnB and GlnD proteins ( Magasanik , 1996 ; Reitzer , 1996a , b ) , phosphorus utilization is controlled by the PhoR -RCB- PhoB sensor kinase -RCB- response-regulator pair ( Wanner , 1996 ) , iron utilization is regulated by the Fur transcription factor ( Earhart , 1996 ; Gralla & Collado-Vides , 1996 ) and sulfur metabolism is controlled by the CysB transcriptional-activator ( Kredich , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11782505" target="_blank">11782505</a>]<br></li>
<li>The MgCl2 concentration was 10 mM ; DNA concentrations were approximately 2 3 105 dpm of 32P per 20-ml reaction mixture ( 0.25 to 0.5 mg/ml ) ; CysB and N-acetyl-L-serine were varied as indicated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>Identical results were obtained when O-acetyl-L-serine was added either together with CysB protein or after a 2-min preincubation of DNA and CysB protein , and N-acetyl-L-serine was as effective as O-acetyl-L-serine ( not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2254265" target="_blank">2254265</a>]<br></li>
<li>With 2 , ug of CysB protein per ml , runoff product formation was markedly stimulated with as little as 0.1 mM N-acetyl-L-serine and was half-maximal with N-acetyl-L-serine concentrations between 0.2 and 0.4 mM ( Fig. 3B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>With 3 jig of CysB protein per ml and 1 mM N-acetyl-L-serine , complex formation was virtually complete , but appreciable increases in free TABLE 1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2105304" target="_blank">2105304</a>]<br></li>
<li>To test this possibility , we investigated the effects of high CysB protein concentrations in a runoff assay and found that with 3 mM N-acetyl-L-serine transcription initiation was maximally stimulated by CysB protein at 3 , ug/ml but was inhibited by approximately 60 and 90 % with CysB protein at 20 and 40 , u.g / ml , respectively ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>Concentrations of CysB protein and O-acetyl-L-serine are indicated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>At a fixed CysB protein concentration of 1 , ug/ml , stimulation of binding was noted with as little as 0.1 mM N-acetyl-L-serine and reached a halfmaximal value at 0.3 to 1 mM ( Fig. 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2105304" target="_blank">2105304</a>]<br></li>
<li>At 1 mM N-acetyl-L-serine and 5 , ug of CysB protein per ml , the inhibitory effects of 4 mM sulfide could be partially overcome by increasing CysB protein to 10 , ug/ml and were completely reversed at 40 , ug/ml ( Fig. 6 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2105304" target="_blank">2105304</a>]<br></li>
<li>At 10 jig of CysB protein per ml , inhibition by approximately 90 % required sulfide concentrations of 0.5 , 1 , and 2 mM at N-acetyl-L-serine concentrations of 0.1 , 0.2 , and 0.3 mM , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2105304" target="_blank">2105304</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here , our results demonstrated that UhpA could perform the similar functions at up-shift high osmotic treatment for 30 min as CysB and Cb1 did in presence of acetylserine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19727945" target="_blank">19727945</a>]<br></li>
<li>CysB positively regulates the genes in sulfur assimilation and cysteine biosynthesis when bound with NAS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18957594" target="_blank">18957594</a>]<br></li>
<li>To test whether environmental sulfur availability affected induction of the CysB regulon in swarm cells , cysJ expression was used to represent CysB regulon activity , as the cells were grown in NBG swarm and swim media with sulfur sources added .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18957594" target="_blank">18957594</a>]<br></li>
<li>The CysB regulon was induced when cells were grown in the presence of the oxidant methyl viologen and the most stressed auxotrophs had increased OxyR and SoxR activity in low-level oxidative-stress conditions compared to wild-type .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20600858" target="_blank">20600858</a>]<br></li>
<li>cysJ and cysH genes were overexpressed in presence of CEF and cysH in presence of MEN in sulfate media and depend on CysB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25637663" target="_blank">25637663</a>]<br></li>
<li>As we previously , reported cysE expression is highly induced in swarm cells ( Turnbull and Surette , 2008 ) independently of CysB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20600858" target="_blank">20600858</a>]<br></li>
<li>1 Department of Biology , University of California at San Diego , La Jolla , CA 92093-0116 , USA 2 Department of Biochemistry , Yamaguchi University School of Medicine , Ube , Yamaguchi , Japan 755 3 Departments of Medicine and Biochemistry , Duke University Medical Center , Durham , NC 27710 , USA Keywords : regulon , transcription , pleiotropic regulators , adenylate cyclase , CysB INTRODUCTION Bacteria require an ample supply of a variety of nutrients to maintain continuous growth .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11782505" target="_blank">11782505</a>]<br></li>
<li>JOURNAL OF BACTERIOLOGY , May 1995 , p. 2343 -- / 95 / $ 04.0010 Copyright q 1995 , American Society for Microbiology Hydroxyl Radical Footprints and Half-Site Arrangements of Sites for the CysB Transcriptional Activator of Salmonella typhimurium Binding MONIKA M. HRYNIEWICZ † AND NICHOLAS M. KREDICH * Departments of Medicine and Biochemistry , Duke University Medical Center , Durham , North Carolina 27710 Received 11 May 1994/Accepted 14 February 1995 CysB is a transcriptional-activator for the cysteine regulon and negatively autoregulates its own gene , cysB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>172 , No. 2 In Vitro Interactions of CysB Protein with the cysJIH Promoter of Salmonella typhimurium : Inhibitory Effects of Sulfide JACEK OSTROWSKI AND NICHOLAS M. KREDICH * Departments of Medicine and Biochemistry , Dluke University Medical Center , Durham , North Carolina 27710 Received 29 September 1989/Accepted 7 November 1989 The cysteine regulon of Salmonella typhimurium is positively regulated by the CysB protein and an inducer , which can be either O-acetyl-L-serine or N-acetyl-L-serine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2105304" target="_blank">2105304</a>]<br></li>
<li>173 , No. 7 Negative Autoregulation of cysB in Salmonella typhimurium : In Vitro Interactions of CysB Protein with the cysB Promoter JACEK OSTROWSKI AND NICHOLAS M. KREDICH * Departments of Medicine and Biochemistry , Duke University Medical Center , Durham , North Carolina 27710 Received 7 November 1990/Accepted 18 January 1991 CysB protein positively regulates genes of the Salmonella typhimurium cysteine regulon and negatively autoregulates cysB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1706701" target="_blank">1706701</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the physiologic signiﬁcance of such repression is questionable , because the CysB concentrations required for transcription inhibition are 40 - to 100-fold higher than those required for activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>Sulﬁde and thiosulfate are antiinducers , probably exerting their effects by competing with N-acetyl - - serine for binding to the CysB activator ( Hryniewicz & Kredich , 1991 ; Ostrowski & Kredich , 1990 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11782505" target="_blank">11782505</a>]<br></li>
<li>Sulfide and thiosulfate are potent anti-inducers of the CysB regulon , by antagonizing binding of NAS to CysB ( Hryniewicz & Kredich , 1991 ; Ostrowski & Kredich , 1990 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18957594" target="_blank">18957594</a>]<br></li>
<li>We reasoned that if cysE upregulation is driving induction of the CysB regulon by increasing NAS levels , adding NAS to swim cells should be able to induce the anti-biotic resistance phenotype in non-swarming cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20600858" target="_blank">20600858</a>]<br></li>
<li>While CysE activity would be normally inhibited by cysteine , elevated expression may overcome this inhibition leading to increased production of the OAS , the precursor for cysteine biosynthesis , and NAS which activates CysB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20600858" target="_blank">20600858</a>]<br></li>
<li>We report here that the cysG gene was not regulated in response to cysteine levels and that its expression did not require the CysB activator protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8383112" target="_blank">8383112</a>]<br></li>
<li>we evidence for negative autoregulation by showing that CysB protein binds to the cysB and inhibits transcription promoter initiation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1706701" target="_blank">1706701</a>]<br></li>
<li>CysB protein also autoregulates its own synthesis by binding to the cysB promoter as a In Salmonella , amino acid biosynthesis is tightly regulated by The cys regulon is under the positive control of CysB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19447191" target="_blank">19447191</a>]<br></li>
<li>CysB protein inhibited transcription initiation at the cysB promoter in an in vitro runoff assay , indicating that cysB is negatively autoregulated by the binding of CysB protein to the cysB promoter , where it acts as a repressor .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1706701" target="_blank">1706701</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although easily demonstrated , inhibition of CysB protein binding by sodium sulfide in the gel shift assay was only modest .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2105304" target="_blank">2105304</a>]<br></li>
<li>In gel mobility shift assays , the mobility of CysB protein-cysP promoter complexes was increased by O-acetyl-L-serine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>N-Acetyl-L-serine could inhibit two-protein complex formation by decreasing the affinity of CysB for CBS-K2 , or it might favor such a complex by causing the first CysB to-bind to CBS-K1 alone , thereby freeing CBS-K2 for further occupancy .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8206845" target="_blank">8206845</a>]<br></li>
<li>Properties of CysB protein binding sites in S. typhimurium cys promoters Regulation by Position relative to Effect of acetyl-L-serne ' on : C transcription CysB protein start site Binding avidity ' Complex mobility ' Positive CBS-J -76 to -35 Transcription activation Increase None Positive CBS-P1 -85 to -41 Transcription activation Increase Increase CBS-P2 -19 to +25 Unknown Increase None CBS-P3 -63 to -11 Unknown Large increase cysK Positive CBS-K1 -78 to -39 Transcription activation Increase None CBS-K2 -115 to -79 Unknown Decrease None cysB Negative CBS-B -10 to +36 Negative autoregulation Decrease None a The data for the cysJIH and cysK promoters are from Monroe et al. ( 34 ) ; the data for the cysB promoter are from Ostrowski and Kredich ( 41 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>These data indicate the presence of two CysB protein-binding sites in the cysK promoter region : one , designated CBS-K1 , at approximately positions -78 to -39 , where binding is stimulated by acetyl-L-serine , and the other , designated CBS-K2 , between positions -115 and -79 , where binding is inhibited by acetyl-L-serine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2254265" target="_blank">2254265</a>]<br></li>
<li>The binding region between positions -76 and -35 was designated CBS-J and is analogous to CBS-K1 in position and by the fact that its binding to CysB protein is stimulated , rather than inhibited , by acetyl-L-serine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2254265" target="_blank">2254265</a>]<br></li>
<li>With higher CysB concentrations and N-acetyl-L-serine , a second tetramer can bind to either CBS-K2 or CBS-P2 , giving two-protein complexes in which the shape of the DNA ( shown as slightly bent ) is not known .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8206845" target="_blank">8206845</a>]<br></li>
<li>With the higher CysB concentrations required for DNase I protection experiments , a second CysB protein molecule can bind specifically to CBS-P2 , resulting in a two-protein complex , but this does not occur with the cysK promoter , in which binding to CBS-K2 is inhibited by acetyl-L-serine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>Acetyl-L-serine changes the conformation of CysB protein in such a way that it binds preferentially to CBS-P1 rather tha to CBS-P3 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our footprinting data indicate that CysB binds to CBS-K2a and CBS-K2c in the absence of N-acetyl-L-serine and to CBS-K2a and CBS-K2b in its presence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>With the cysP promoter , our footprinting and stoichiometric binding data indicate that in the absence of N-acetyl-L-serine , a single CysB tetramer binds to three halfsites , CBS-P1a , CBS-P1b , and CBS-P3b ( Fig. 8 and 9C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>Inhibition of binding to CBS-K2 by acetyl-L-serine would diminish or completely eliminate DNA bending and result in formation of the fast complex , in which CysB protein is bound only to CBS-K1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2254265" target="_blank">2254265</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our data indicate that the slow complex represents binding of CysB protein to both CBS-K1 and CBS-K2 and that the fast complex found in the presence of acetyl-L-serine is due to-binding to CBS-K1 alone .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2254265" target="_blank">2254265</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since N-acetyl-L-serine inhibits binding to CBS-P3 and stimulates binding to CBS-P1 and CBS-P2 , the two-protein complex noted in the presence of CysB this effector probably contains a separate tetramer at each of the last two sites ( Fig. 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8206845" target="_blank">8206845</a>]<br></li>
<li>We propose that binding of CysB protein to the CBS-P3 site in the absence of acetyl-L-serine causes the DNA to bend at a point approximately midway between CBS-P1 and CBS-P2 , resulting in anomalously slow electrophoretic mobility and DNase I hypersensitivity at positions -30 to -27 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>Protection between 2115 and 2136 was very faint at CysB concentrations of lower than 10 to 30 mg/ml , at which most complexes have been shown to contain a single CysB tetramer , which is bound to CBS-K1 in the presence of N-acetyl-L-serine and to both CBS-K1 and the downstream portion of CBS-K2 in its absence ( 18 , 31 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , CysB appears to-bind to CBS-Ba and CBS-Bb both in the absence and in the presence of N-acetyl-L-serine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the higher affinities of CysB for the cysK and cysP promoters may be related more to the presence of secondary binding sites than to differences in affinities between the transcription activator sites CBS-P1 , CBS-K1 , and CBS-J .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8206845" target="_blank">8206845</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of N-acetyl-L-serine , a single CysB tetramer binds to both the CBS-K1 and CBS-K2 sites of the cysK promoter or to CBS-P3 in the cysP promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8206845" target="_blank">8206845</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the case of the cysP promoter , one-protein complexes in the presence of N-acetyl-L-serine are most likely to contain CysB at CBS-P1 , which has a sixfold-greater binding affinity than CBS-P2 ( 24 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8206845" target="_blank">8206845</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although CysB protein binds to CBS-K1 and CBS-J in the absence of inducer , in vitro transcription from the cysJIH promoter has been shown to require the additional presence of either O-acetyl-L-serine or N-acetyl-L-serine , even at CysB protein concentrations that ensure total occupancy of CBS-J ( 25 , 26 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2254265" target="_blank">2254265</a>]<br></li>
<li>This correlation holds true for the CBS-P2 sequence , which is similar to that of CBS-P1 and also binds CysB protein more tightly in the presence of acetyl-L-serine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>DNase I footprints indicate that these species contain CysB bound to either CBS-K1 alone or CBS-P1 alone in the presence of N-acetyl-L-serine ( 24 , 39 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8206845" target="_blank">8206845</a>]<br></li>
<li>From gel mobility shift studies , we estimate that the CysB protein concentrations necessary for half-maximal binding in the presence of O-acetyl-L-serine are approximately 0.6 , 0.1 , and 0.1 , ug/ml , respectively , for fragments containing either CBS-P2 alone , CBS-P1 alone , or both sites together .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since accessory sites appear to increase binding afﬁnity in the absence of N-acetyl-L-serine ( 17 , 18 ) , we speculate that their physiologic function is to sequester CysB at cys promoters when sulfur is replete in order to ensure a rapid response to sulfur limitation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>We conclude , therefore , that binding alone is insufficient to stimulate transcription and that the three - to eightfold increase in binding caused by inducer at lower CysB protein concentrations is a consequence of qualitative changes leading to formation of a transcription initiation complex .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2105304" target="_blank">2105304</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , CysB appears to recognize speciﬁc determinants on either side of position 250 and is sufﬁciently ﬂexible to contact them and activate promoters in which the distances between these determinants vary by 1 bp .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>Genes of E. coli and S. Typhimurium involved in the sulfate / thiosulfate assimilatory pathway are shown according to the scheme of Kredich ; those activated by CysB ( as transcription units : sbp , cysPTWA , cysDNC , cysJIH , cysK , and cysM ) are highlighted in dark gray .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19727945" target="_blank">19727945</a>]<br></li>
<li>cysJIH expression is upregulated by CysB in response to ceftriaxone or menadione In order to correlate a possible regulation of cysJIH by CysB in ROS treatment , we evaluated the transcript levels of cysJ , cysI and cysH genes in wild type and DcysB strains in sulfate medium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25637663" target="_blank">25637663</a>]<br></li>
<li>The requirement for sulfur limitation appears to be due to an anti-inducer effect of sulfide , which interferes with the ability of CysB protein and inducer to activate gene expression both in vivo and in vitro ( 14 , 15 , 26 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2254265" target="_blank">2254265</a>]<br></li>
<li>These effects are in contrast to those observed in studies of positively regulated cys promoters , in which N-acetyl-L-serine stimulates binding and causes CysB protein to activate transcription initiation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1706701" target="_blank">1706701</a>]<br></li>
<li>Inhibition competitive stimulatory effects of acetyl-L-serine , suggesting that sulfide interacts directly with CysB protein , perhaps at the same binding site as that for inducer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2105304" target="_blank">2105304</a>]<br></li>
<li>A model showing relationships between half-site arrangements and the effects of N-acetyl-L-serine on CysB binding afﬁnity and on DNA bending .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>The effects of N-acetyl-L-serine and sulfide on binding of CysB protein appeared to be competitive with each other , since inhibition by 1 to 4 mM sodium sulfide could be overcome by increasing N-acetyl-L-serine from 1 mM to 10 mM ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2105304" target="_blank">2105304</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vitro binding of CysB protein to the cysK promoter induces DNA bending , which is diminished or eliminated by acetyl-L-serine ( 34 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vitro transcription initiation from the cysP promoter was shown to require both CysB protein and either O-acetyl-L-serine or N-acetyl-L-serine , which act as inducers , and was inhibited by the anti-inducer sulfide .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION The studies reported here demonstrate that CysB protein binds to the cysJIH promoter region in vitro and that such binding is stimulated by the inducers N-acetyl-L-serine and O-acetyl-L-serine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2105304" target="_blank">2105304</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vitro studies have demonstrated that CysB protein binds to a site immediately preceding the -35 regions of the positively regulated cysJIH and cysK promoters and that binding is stimulated by acetyl-L-serine , i.e. , O-acetyl-L-serine or N-acetyl-L-serine ( 34 , 40 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast to results obtained with the cysJIH and cysK promoters , which showed that specific binding of CysB protein was stimulated by the inducer N-acetyl-L-serine or O-acetyl-L-serine ( 27 , 30 ) , binding to the cysB promoter region was inhibited by N-acetyl-L-serine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1706701" target="_blank">1706701</a>]<br></li>
<li>The combination of CysB protein and acetyl-L-serine markedly stimulates in vitro transcription initiation from both promoters , and this effect is inhibited by the anti-inducer sulfide ( 32 , 39 , 40 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>The reversal of sulfide inhibition by CysB protein or N-acetyl-L-serine indicates that such inhibition is specific for transcription initiated from the cysJIH promoter and is not due to nonspecific effects of sulfide on transcription in general .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2105304" target="_blank">2105304</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ability of sulfide to inhibit binding of CysB protein to the cysJIH promoter parallels its effects on transcription initiation and is competitive with N-acetyl-L-serine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2105304" target="_blank">2105304</a>]<br></li>
<li>CysB binds the inducer , N-acetyl-L-serine ( NAS ) , the product of a non-enzymic rearrangement of OAS ( Sturgill et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18957594" target="_blank">18957594</a>]<br></li>
<li>The gene product of cysE , serine acetyltranferase , produces OAS which can non-enzymatically rearrange to form the CysB inducer , NAS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20600858" target="_blank">20600858</a>]<br></li>
<li>This may help to explain some of the mutagenic potency and mutational spectra of MX ; however , it does not Gene Nitric oxide synthesis and detoxiﬁcation Carnitine metabolism Molybdenum metabolism Cold shock Indirect activator of L-rhamnose operon Integration host factor Sulfur assimilation via cysteine biosynthesis Response to DNA damage Cyclic AMP receptor protein growth regulation Global anaerobic regulator Regulates response to the redox conditions of growth BA-1 NsrR 2.0E-02 3.4E-02 4.4E-02 4.4E-02 CaiF ModE CspA RhaR 4.3E-02 5.6E-09 BA-4 IHF MX CysB 1.1E-07 6.3E-06 LexA CRP FNR ArcA a of the consequences of these alterations .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19598237" target="_blank">19598237</a>]<br></li>
<li>Induction of the CysB regulon by addition of exogenous inducer resulted in elevated antibiotic resistance independently of swarming .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20600858" target="_blank">20600858</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , the effects of loss of CysB were much less pronounced under conditions of catabolite repression than in the absence of a catabolite-repressing carbon source , and cAMP largely reversed the effect of the loss of CysB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11782505" target="_blank">11782505</a>]<br></li>
<li>No change in growth was observed in the presence of NAS , indicating that the effect of induction of the CysB regulon on antibiotic resistance was independent of cell density ( Butler et al. , 2010 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20600858" target="_blank">20600858</a>]<br></li>
<li>cysK has a significant level of basal expression in the absence of CysB activation as observed in swim cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18957594" target="_blank">18957594</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results show that : i ) in presence of sulfate as the sole sulfur source , both the cysJIH operon and cysB play a role in detoxiﬁcation against ROS ; ii ) in presence of cysteine as an organic source of sulfur , only CysB seems to be required .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25637663" target="_blank">25637663</a>]<br></li>
<li>By assuming that the most rapidly migrating complex in the presence of N-acetyl-L-serine has a mobility that is very close to P2 , we calculated bend angles of 102 and 96 ° with the cysK and cysP promoters , respectively , in the absence of N-acetyl-L-serine and of approximately 50 ° for both promoters in the presence of N-acetyl-L-serine Mean + SE 4.2 + 0.8 cysK 0.09 37 1 3.6 3.7 3.4 3.4 0.18 0.27 0.09 0.18 0.27 0.09 0.18 0.09 0.18 0.09 0.09 37 37 41 41 41 34 34 41 41 41 41 3.8 4.2 3.4 3.4 3.8 3.0 4.3 5.4 5.4 4.4 4.0 + 0.8 2 7.2 3.2 3.5 10.0 3.0 3.5 3.8 4.6 4.1 4.1 3.7 + 0.5 3 9.6 10.1 4dl 10.9 10.4 5d ] 10.2 + 0.7 9.2 + 1.8 Mean + SE cysP 0.09 0.18 0.27 0.18 0.18 0.18 0.18 0.18 0.18 0.18 0.18 0.18 0.18 55 55 3.8 3.1 2.8 2.8 3.4 3.2 3.8 3.7 3.0 2.8 4.7 4.5 3.4 3.2 1 55 26 42 55 84 110 55 110 37 55 55 2 4.2 4.1 3.9 3.2 3.6 5.1 4.5 ¬ 3d ¬ ¬ 4 7.3 2.9 3.8 9.5 9.5 7.3 Mean + SE 3.8 + 0.2 CysB protein and DNA were determined by measuring the content of 35S and 32P radiolabel , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8206845" target="_blank">8206845</a>]<br></li>
<li>DNA bending may be a mechanism for sequestering CysB at certain promoter sites by increasing their affinity for this protein in the absence of N-acetyl-L-serine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8206845" target="_blank">8206845</a>]<br></li>
<li>A third possibility is that CysB does not bend DNA at all and that changes in electrophoretic mobility simply reflect binding by different amounts of protein , e.g. , a slowly migrating two-protein complex in the absence of N-acetyl-L-serine and a more rapidly migrating one-protein complex in its presence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8206845" target="_blank">8206845</a>]<br></li>
<li>CysB protein creates hypersensitive sites in this region ; these sites disappear in the presence of O-acetyl-L-serine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909324" target="_blank">1909324</a>]<br></li>
<li>CysB positively regulates at least six different promoters within the cysteine regulon by activating transcription initiation in the presence of the inducer N-acetyl-L-serine ( 32 ) and negatively autoregulates its own expression from cysB ( 3 , 23 , 34 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>CTS-1 , a part of the CysB regulon , accounts for the majority of cysteine uptake , and is repressed by growth on cysteine and other reduced sulfur sources .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18957594" target="_blank">18957594</a>]<br></li>
<li>But , it is noted that , the presence of acetylserine was the indispensable coinducer of the CysB and Cb1 regulators of E. coli and Salmonella [ 9 , 12 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19727945" target="_blank">19727945</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this work , we propose a model in which H2S production against ROS depends on the sulfur source and the presence of the transcriptional-regulator of the cysteine regulon , CysB , and the products of the cysJIH operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25637663" target="_blank">25637663</a>]<br></li>
<li>With our 19-bp half-site model , binding of a CysB tetramer to an activation site would leave two subunits potentially free for interactions with other half-sites , and we believe that one of these is so employed during bending of the cysK and cysP promoters in the absence of N-acetyl-L-serine , in which binding occurs to both an activation site and part of an adjacent accessory site ( see below ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>( A ) N-acetyl-L-serine stimulation of binding when half-sites are convergent and separated by 1 to 3 bp ; ( B ) N-acetyl-L-serine inhibition of binding to sites with divergently oriented half-sites separated by one or two turns of the helix ; ( C ) regions in the cysP and cysK promoters that contain a half-site oriented toward an activation site and separated from it by 12 or 13 bp are bent by CysB but less so in the presence of N-acetyl-L-serine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the single experiment in which C-2 complexes could be quantified , ratios of 9.5 and 7.3 were obtained in the absence and presence of N-acetyl-L-serine , respectively , indicating that these complexes contain two CysB tetramers per DNA molecule .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8206845" target="_blank">8206845</a>]<br></li>
